  <!-- ── Key Features ── -->
  <h2 id="features">Key Features</h2>

  <h3>Automatic (Self-Cleaning) Centrifuges</h3>

  <p>
    Self-cleaning disc-stack centrifuges are engineered for continuous, unattended operation. The centrifuge bowl periodically ejects accumulated sludge at timed intervals controlled by the system PLC. This eliminates manual cleaning downtime and enables 24/7 processing capability.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Continuous flow-through operation</li>
    <li>Automatic sludge ejection on timed cycles</li>
    <li>No operator intervention required during processing</li>
    <li>Ideal for high-volume waste oil applications</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Filtering (Heavy Sludge Handling) Centrifuges</h3>

  <p>
    For waste oil with exceptionally high sludge content, filtering-type centrifuges offer extended processing capacity before requiring manual bowl cleaning. These units are well suited for batch processing or applications where the solids load exceeds the ejection capacity of self-cleaning models.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Extended sludge holding capacity</li>
    <li>Handles high-viscosity sludge and heavy contaminants</li>
    <li>Manual bowl cleaning between processing runs</li>
    <li>Lower operating cost for batch applications</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Applications ── -->
  <h2 id="applications">Applications</h2>

  <h3>Used Motor Oil Processing</h3>

  <p>
    Used motor oil contains suspended metals (aluminum, silicon, iron), carbon particles, ash, and water. Disc-stack centrifuges effectively remove these contaminants, producing clean base oil suitable for re-refining or direct reuse as industrial fuel.
  </p>

  <p>
    Our centrifuge systems <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-remove-metals-ash-used-oil/">remove metals and ash from used engine oil</a>, achieving output quality that meets fuel specifications and re-refining feedstock standards.
  </p>

  <h3>Commercial Waste Oil Recovery</h3>

  <p>
    Commercial waste oil collectors process thousands of gallons daily from automotive shops, fleet maintenance facilities, and industrial operations. Centrifuge-based processing replaces labor-intensive settling and filtration with continuous, automated separation.
  </p>

  <p>
    A single centrifuge system can process <strong>500 to over 10,000 gallons per day</strong>, dramatically reducing labor costs while producing a higher-quality finished product.
  </p>

  <!-- ── How It Works ── -->
  <h2 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h2>

  <p>
    Waste oil centrifuges use high-speed rotation to generate intense centrifugal force &mdash; up to <strong>8,000 Gs</strong> or more. This force separates the waste oil into its component phases based on density differences:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Clean oil</strong> (lightest phase) collects at the center of the bowl and discharges through the light-phase outlet</li>
    <li><strong>Water</strong> (heavier phase) migrates outward and exits through a separate heavy-phase outlet</li>
    <li><strong>Sludge and solids</strong> (heaviest phase) accumulate at the bowl periphery and are periodically ejected</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Automatic vs. Manual Models</h3>

  <p>
    <strong>Automatic (self-cleaning) models</strong> feature hydraulically actuated bowl mechanisms that periodically open to eject accumulated sludge. The ejection cycle is PLC-controlled and occurs while the centrifuge continues to rotate at full speed &mdash; no downtime required.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Manual (filtering) models</strong> accumulate solids in the bowl until the sludge space is full, at which point the machine is shut down for manual bowl cleaning. These are better suited for applications with lower solids content or batch processing.
  </p>

